Now, I should stress that Marc Rich always claimed that he did nothing wrong, that he did not

00:21:34.547 --> 00:21:41.237
knowingly evade taxes, and there was no legal reason for his Swiss company not to trade with Iran.

00:21:42.707 --> 00:21:49.677
He died in June of 2013, almost exactly 10 years ago, leaving behind a complicated legacy.

00:21:50.937 --> 00:21:55.197
He was first and foremost a trader, a man who put together

00:21:55.467 --> 00:21:59.957
buyer and seller, asking few questions and casting no judgement.

00:22:00.817 --> 00:22:04.257
He was the man in the middle, simply providing a service.

00:22:05.677 --> 00:22:10.437
That service was an incredibly valuable one; it turned him into a billionaire.

00:22:11.805 --> 00:22:15.457
At his height, he controlled a large part of the world’s oil supply.

00:22:16.437 --> 00:22:22.907
If you drove in a car, train or aeroplane at any point from 1960 to the

00:22:22.907 --> 00:22:28.667
mid 1990s, there’s a high chance it was powered by oil sold by Marc Rich.

00:22:29.627 --> 00:22:35.967
Now, you might agree or disagree with his actions and methods, but you have

00:22:35.967 --> 00:22:41.177
to admit that nobody was more deserving of the nickname “The King of Oil”.

